goals.question: What is the relationship between fertility and life expectancy?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of fertility vs life_expect
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between fertility and life expectancy. We can see if there is a trend of higher fertility leading to lower life expectancy or vice versa.

goals.question: What is the distribution of fertility rates across different countries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of fertility rates across different countries. We can see if there are any outliers or if the distribution is skewed.

goals.question: What is the distribution of life expectancy across different countries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of life expectancy across different countries. We can see if there are any outliers or if the distribution is skewed.

goals.question: How does the predicted fertility rate compare to the actual fertility rate?
goals.visualization: line chart of fertility vs p_fertility
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand how accurate the predicted fertility rate is compared to the actual fertility rate. We can see if there is any trend of overestimation or underestimation.

goals.question: How does the predicted life expectancy compare to the actual life expectancy?
goals.visualization: line chart of life_expect vs p_life_expect
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand how accurate the predicted life expectancy is compared to the actual life expectancy. We can see if there is any trend of overestimation or underestimation.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    plt.scatter(data['fertility'], data['life_expect'])
    plt.xlabel('Fertility')
    plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between fertility and life expectancy?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['fertility'].plot(kind='hist', bins=20, color='green', alpha=0.5)
    plt.axvline(data['fertility'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['fertility'].median()))
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of fertility rates across different countries?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data.sort_values(by='year')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.plot(data['year'], data['fertility'], label='Actual Fertility Rate')
    ax.plot(data['year'], data['p_fertility'], label='Predicted Fertility Rate')
    ax.legend()
    plt.title('How does the predicted fertility rate compare to the actual fertility rate?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
